() => { const __payload = {"419c196b-6e31-4345-84d3-562a245f008c__systemfield_name": "Cyrus Shekari", "419c196b-6e31-4345-84d3-562a245f008c__systemfield_email": "cyshekari@gmail.com", "419c196b-6e31-4345-84d3-562a245f008c_d9737c83-64f5-449f-ab07-e88084f9a1f5": "346-804-0227", "419c196b-6e31-4345-84d3-562a245f008c_fd10385e-b060-42aa-83e9-a6b618c9d6ac": "At Microsoft, I built a Resilience Automation Platform that cut operational toil by 30% and freed engineering capacity for higher-impact customer work - essentially the same trade-off Deepgram's Applied Engineering team is trying to make. I also built an AI agent that reduced planning cycle time by 39% and increased drill capacity by 21%, and I developed self-service runbooks that let customers resolve complex issues independently and reduced escalation load on senior engineers. The problems Deepgram is solving - scaling technical support through automation, building tools that let customers self-serve, and keeping engineers focused on high-value engagements - are problems I've been working on directly.\n\nWhat draws me to Deepgram specifically is that voice AI is a genuinely hard infrastructure problem, not just a wrapper on existing models. The fact that Deepgram has processed over 50,000 years of audio and built voice-native foundation models from the ground up - not retrofitted from text - tells me the technical depth here is real. I want to work at the layer where AI meets production infrastructure at scale, and Deepgram is building exactly that foundation for the next wave of voice applications. The AI-first operating culture also appeals to me - I've already been building AI tooling into my own workflows and want to be somewhere that treats that as a baseline expectation, not a differentiator.", "419c196b-6e31-4345-84d3-562a245f008c_fa3d2b59-95c7-4ecf-9be5-f2285bd81c53": "My core approach is to start with discovery before jumping to solutions. At Microsoft, I conducted discovery with 20+ service teams to quantify exactly 81 hours of manual toil per region launch. That number didn't come from assumptions - it came from structured conversations where I asked teams to walk me through their actual workflows step by step. That data then drove a roadmap targeting the highest-impact automation paths, which ultimately generated $3M in accelerated revenue and cut region launch time by 28%. The specificity of the finding is what made the solution credible and got cross-functional buy-in across 140+ engineering teams with competing priorities.\n\nI've also used customer escalations as a signal, not just a ticket queue. When I saw recurring failure patterns across support escalations at Azure, I collaborated with engineering teams to advocate for roadmap changes that reduced repeat incident volume by 18%. That required translating raw support data into a product argument - showing engineering why a pattern mattered and what fixing it would actually cost versus prevent. Similarly, I ran 11+ user interviews with Azure service teams to surface API workflow gaps, and those findings shipped as intent-based YAML generation features the following quarter. The through line in all of these is treating customer pain as structured data that can drive technical decisions, rather than noise to be managed.", "419c196b-6e31-4345-84d3-562a245f008c_a7550857-2968-4e68-8b65-d15b5c277c26": "The most durable thing I've built for scale is documentation that actually removes the need to ask me. At Microsoft, I developed technical runbooks and self-service documentation that were adopted across 6 partner teams. The goal wasn't to write comprehensive guides - it was to identify the specific moments where engineers were reaching out to escalate and eliminate those moments with targeted, actionable content. That reduced escalation load on senior engineers and let the broader team handle more complex engagements without bottlenecks.\n\nBeyond documentation, I've leaned heavily on automation to multiply capacity. I built an AI agent to automate drill planning workflows, which cut planning cycle time by 39% and increased drill capacity by 21%. That's a direct example of using tooling to let one person do what previously required more cycles or more people. I also built a Power BI dashboard that tracked operational toil across 140+ teams, which gave leadership a scalable way to prioritize support investments without needing me in every conversation. The pattern across all of these is the same: identify where expertise is the bottleneck, then build something that removes that bottleneck - whether it's a doc, a dashboard, or an automated system - so the team can scale without linearly scaling headcount.", "419c196b-6e31-4345-84d3-562a245f008c_9881ae73-1533-43a7-bb73-8d81b79c1038": "The most impactful AI system I've built is an AI agent I designed and deployed at Microsoft to automate drill planning workflows for Azure's resilience testing program. Before this, scheduling and planning each resilience drill was a heavily manual process - coordinating across customer teams, mapping dependencies, validating readiness criteria, and generating documentation. It was a cycle that consumed significant engineering time and capped how many drills we could run.\n\nI built the agent to handle the repeatable, structured portions of that workflow end to end. It ingested inputs about the target environment, dependency graph, and readiness requirements, then generated a complete drill plan - including scheduling recommendations, stakeholder notifications, and pre-drill checklists - without requiring manual assembly at each step. I used LLM-based reasoning for the parts of planning that required interpreting ambiguous inputs or adapting to environment-specific constraints, and layered deterministic logic on top for the outputs that needed to be consistent and auditable.\n\nThe measurable outcome was a 39% reduction in planning cycle time and a 21% increase in drill capacity - meaning we could run more drills with the same team, and engineers could redirect the recovered time toward the complex, customer-facing escalations that actually required human judgment. That's the framing I care most about with AI tooling: not automation for its own sake, but freeing high-skill people to do the work only they can do.", "419c196b-6e31-4345-84d3-562a245f008c_eb96ea6d-a07d-4512-b1e6-b32980498953": "https://linkedin.com/in/cyshekari"}; return ((textFields) => {
  const out = {resolved: [], missing: []};
